WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Well, thank you everyone. I appreciate everybody being here.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.000
My name is Edgar. I am a software developer, software engineer at Posit.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
I've been with Posit for several years and I'm very excited to see all of you today.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Usually I talk about work that I've been doing, but this time around I'm going to be talking about work that others have been doing inside Posit.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:34.000
So I'll be standing on the shoulders of giants. Some of them are here today, so I really appreciate Joe's work.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:45.000
The first thing I want to talk about regarding making it easier for us to be able to work with databases is improvements to the odbc package.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Improvements that are now available in CRAN that you should be able to take advantage of.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
So the first improvement that I want to talk about, other than of course this really cool logo that we just started adding,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:12.000
is this new thing that we have with odbc where before whenever you were trying to connect to odbc you needed about 10 arguments to be able to do so.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:21.000
This is something that was funny because I personally had to go and try to connect and so that way we can actually have it documented in our solutions site.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So we figured that we needed several different arguments such as first of all starting with the odbc call that we would do in DBI.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Then of course we will call the driver. We need to tell odbc where the driver is.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:46.000
The host, meaning the location where we want to, where our workspace is in Databricks.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And also the token that we're going to use, the path is called a personal access token.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Also the SQL warehouse location inside Databricks, the port that we're going to use, the authentication mechanism, protocol, thrift stamp transport, the SSL and UID,

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.000
which is weird because AuthMech usually means token, but anyway, they want all of these.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
In order for you to be able to connect, we had to have all of them, which we get used to it.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
As users, we just get used to it and I am sure it happens to all of us.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
We connect one time and we start a new project with what we do.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
It's just we copy the old code and put it in a new project and we continue.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And what happens after that? Well, we can share that code to somebody that doesn't have our same setup.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
And guess what? It doesn't work. And we start seeing the pains there.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:47.000
So now we have a new function inside ODBC called Databricks.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:57.000
So Databricks sets sensible defaults for us and also it lets us deal with only one of the arguments that we needed to pass,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
which is that SQL warehouse path that is inside Databricks.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.000
This is a big departure from how usually we have dealt with ODBC.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Usually ODBC was sort of kind of like behind the curtain kind of package that we would only deal with only if we really needed to.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
The only thing that we wanted to do was to work with the driver and also do the type conversions, right?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
From what your database has to R, right?

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.000
If you have a character, an integer, a double, how are you going to deal with all that?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:38.000
That's all inside ODBC, which adapts itself based on the type of connection that you have, let's say Oracle, Teradata and such.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:49.000
But this time around, we're extending ODBC where now you can actually use a function that instead of ODBC, you just call Databricks.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
This is work that Aaron Jacobs did.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So it was just outstanding, you know, because now it makes it so much easier for us to connect.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And of course, once we figured we could do this, we could see that passing that function and then using that path would get us connected.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:23.000
We know that there's going to be locations inside our laptops, inside our systems that will be the most common where the drivers are.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So not only it does the sensible defaults, it actually also is smart enough to look for the driver in locations that are going to be default, right?

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
So let's go ahead and look for them, right?

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:43.000
The other thing that it does is that once it starts looking and finding your environment variables that you haven't set up in your machine,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
then it will actually decide what kind of authentication method you are using and just use that.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
So if you have a path like your personal authentication token, it'll use that.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:02.000
But if it detects like if you're on workbench and you have the Databricks integration set up, it'll just use that.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So you don't need to tell anything else.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
It'll just connect.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:15.000
It'll pass your credentials and then it will use those defaults for the other arguments that are part of it,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.000
including the protocol and the SSL and all this other stuff that we're talking about.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
For example, the UID changes, right? It's not token anymore if you're using workbench, for example.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
So it does all that for you automatically.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And of course, any of these arguments can be overwritten by you.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So let's say that you have a driver that you're testing is maybe in a different spot.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.000
Well, just still use ODBC Databricks and then just overwrite the driver location.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:48.000
It's like it won't send you back where you have to use ODBC, ODBC again, which is amazing.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Once this was done, then, oh yeah, I forgot about this.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
This is another thing that's cool.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:04.000
So if you attended the keynote, James touched on that particular function.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
That's why it sounds familiar.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:12.000
But one of the things that because of time, I'm sure, wasn't really mentioned is the fact that inside Mac,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:23.000
there was actually an issue, an issue that has to do with the driver needing a specific entry in an INI file.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
That if it's not there, it's not going to work.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:33.000
So as part of the documentation, we added all the steps that you needed to do, like you see right here, in order to fix that.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Well, with the new function, the ODBC Databricks, it will automatically do all that for us.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:47.000
Other than, of course, it won't install the Unix ODBC, but everything else it'll do automatically.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
It'll make the entry that you need and automatically connect you.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
It's like you don't even have to think about it.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.000
That's why if you have used this Databricks function recently and you haven't used it before,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:07.000
you didn't suffer in Mac, that's because, you know, Aaron made sure that that was something that you didn't have to worry about.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:12.000
So you are one of the blessed ones.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:19.000
Another function that we are actually rather Simon and Aaron and Hadley added is the Snowflake function,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:24.000
which, as you would imagine, would help you connect to Snowflake, which is also amazing, right?

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Now we open the door. It's not only ODBC anymore.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
We can expand it to other ones.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Snowflake, the same idea before you needed several arguments.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:42.000
And now if you have all the environment variables set up, you probably will only need to call the function.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So you say DB connect and ODBC Snowflake and you're good to go.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Again, it's really cool because this will allow us to be very flexible in how you connect.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Because, for example, if you were connecting through the browser based SSO that Snowflake has,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:10.000
and if you're on your desktop, it will work for you as well as reverting back to the more traditional username and password.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
I wave my hands all over the place.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And it will, you know, you can just adapt it, right?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Again, you won't go back to ODBC, ODBC. You just add or overwrite, rather, those two entries.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
So same thing what Snowflake does. It does look for the driver.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And I didn't mention this for Databricks.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.000
The driver, automatic driver lookup works for Linux and Mac machines.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.000
But it does the same thing. It looks for the driver.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:48.000
Also determines the authentication that you're using and does the right setup, the right defaults that you need.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
So you don't even need to think about them. Passes your credentials.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.000
And what you saw earlier, you don't need to worry about having to revert back.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
You just use the Snowflake or Databricks and can overwrite anything.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
The other thing I want to talk about is the DB connection in Positron.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
I'm actually really excited about this.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:15.000
Whenever we were talking about this new IDE internally at Positron,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
I was like, we need the database connection.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Please let us have it, you know, version one, if we can.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And I was really excited when that was decided on.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
So as you recall, we have the RStudio Connections pane.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And this is where the words I use when I type.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
They just type themselves. The beloved thing just came out.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.000
Like, I didn't think about it when I saw it. I had already written it.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
I've been using RStudio for so long.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
And when it came out, it actually came out first, if I'm correct,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
with the Sparkly R package.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
And when I saw that, it just blew my mind.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:55.000
And then when it was expanded to use the other databases through dbplyr and dbi,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
it was, like, just amazing, right?

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Because I used to have, you know, three screens.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
I had RStudio, I had Microsoft SQL Studio,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
and I had Outlook open 24-7 when I was at work.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And now I can just merge it into one, right?

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
Because I don't have to worry about going back and saying,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
okay, what's the name of the table again?

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
What are the fields that it has? I can just do it all inside the RStudio IDE.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And I just thought that was such a big productivity increase that we can gain

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
that it just, like, blew my mind.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And it did change my productivity.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
I didn't have to think about it after just getting used to it.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Because I'm able to navigate, right, right through the catalogs,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.000
the schemas, and the tables that I have access to.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
When I make the R connection to the database, it automatically is there.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And also, as you recall, you can actually preview the names of the fields,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:47.000
the types.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
I can also preview data.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And, of course, that's now available in Positron, right?

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So, to me, this is great.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
The actual look of it is amazing.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
It's very well integrated with the look of VS Code and Positron.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And we have the same functionality, day one, right?

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Again, all this knowledge that we have gathered over time with RStudio

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
is now being implemented here rather quick in Positron.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So, it's available in the public beta.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
The same idea, we can navigate through a database structure.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
We can preview the field names.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And just like I said, nice integrated look.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Remember the preview that we can have on the first thousand rows

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
in RStudio?

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Well, we can do the same thing in Positron.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
But, in Positron, we get this super cool thing

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:47.000
where it does some analysis, some stats on the 1,000 rows

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
that it's previewing and gives you some idea of how well populated

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:58.000
the column is, of course, all the names and different types.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
Before, you had to scroll to the side and look at the names, right?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And kind of infer the types.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
And here, you just see the types that they are listed.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
So, it's just amazing.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:14.000
It also tells you how many NAs there are, how many null values.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.000
And you see that in that inline graph

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.000
that, for example, top one, kind of hard to read, says 7%.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
Here's a closer look of it where you can see it.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So, this is where you can see it, where you can click on it,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.000
and then you can go and see just the data.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And the other very cool thing is that it works with Python, right?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So, before, if you wanted to do some Python work in RStudio

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
and if you wanted some database work, it was that you had to go to reticulate

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
and do all those sorts of things as we had to.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
But because of how Positron works and how Daniel actually coded this,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
is that it's basically available for both.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
If you connect via SQLAlchemy to the database,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
it will create the same type of connection.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So, here you see an example that I have connected to that same Databricks cluster,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
or excuse me, SQL Warehouse.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
I created an engine. You see that?

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And that engine object right there that I created with my code

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:32.000
will be cataloged inside our variable environment as an engine

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
and it will give it a specific icon.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Once you click on that icon, then you'll see a new connection

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:45.000
in your connections pane that has the SQLAlchemy prefix

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
and the type of connection that it is.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
So, that's all you have to do. You connect, you click on that icon,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
and now you see it, which I thought is just so great.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Then you see the same idea, right?

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.000
You can expand on the catalogs and be able to see the schemas,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
get down to the tables.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:11.000
You can also click on a specific table and see the exact same steps, right?

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
So, imagine you're not even using R, you're just using Python,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
and you get the same goodies directly from Python.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:29.000
So, I really appreciate your attention, and if you have any questions.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Yeah, so I'll start off with a couple of questions from the crowd.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
Give me a second.

